The paper deals with noncooperative game-theoretic tools for resource allocation problems in communications and networking, which suggests that it could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of matrices in the complex domain, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the application of the developed methods to cognitive radio systems, which suggests that it could belong to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper introduces a novel class of distributed algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
